South African gold mining firm Gold Fields is expecting a staggering 730- 780% growth in headline earnings after making a loss in the period prior, the company said in a trading update.Earnings per share (EPS) for the 12 months ended December 2016 are expected to be between 160% and 170% higher than the loss per share of $0.31 (R4.11) reported for the 12 months ended December 31, 2015.The company said that the increases in EPS, HEPS and normalised earnings are primarily driven by an 8% increase in the $ gold price year on year and lower net operating costs in local currencies as well as the impact of converting these costs at weaker exchange rates. Gold Fields is an unhedged, global producer of gold with eight operating mines in Australia, Ghana, Peru and South Africa with attributable annual gold production of about 2 million ounces. It has attributable mineral reserves of around 46 million ounces and mineral resources of around 102 million ounces.Attributable copper mineral reserves total 532m (R8.8 trillion) and mineral resources 5.9m. Gold Fields has a primary listing on the JSE, with secondary listings on the New York Stock Exchange and the Swiss Exchange.-Thelma Ngoma|thelman@thenewage.co.za